Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: The core challenge in motion-to-triplane mapping lies in establishing a meaningful, deformable correspondence between dynamic motion signals (e.g., from video or pose sequences) and high-fidelity 3D-aware feature representations—specifically tri-plane features used in modern NeRF-based models—without relying on rigid 3D parametric priors like SMPL or 3DMM. Existing methods either depend on such priors for correspondence or learn implicit mappings that lack interpretability and efficiency. Inspired by Paper 2’s PlaneDict concept, which uses a dictionary of orthogonal plane bases to encode motion, I propose a more generalizable and structured approach: instead of continuous latent additions, we discretize the deformation space into a *sparse latent deformation codebook*, where each codeword represents a canonical, interpretable deformation mode (e.g., bending, rotating, translating specific parts). This enables efficient, modular, and composable deformation synthesis by selecting and combining only a few relevant codewords per input motion condition. Unlike dense correspondence learning (Paper 1) or multi-space modeling (Paper 3), this method avoids expensive point-wise matching or complex temporal fusion, focusing instead on learning a compact, reusable set of deformation primitives directly in tri-plane space. The key innovation is the integration of vector quantization (VQ) into tri-plane deformation learning, enabling sparse activation, better generalization across unseen motions, and improved disentanglement between identity, pose, and articulation. This approach is especially powerful for few-shot and one-shot reenactment scenarios where parametric models fail due to domain mismatch or lack of alignment.

