  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework titled 'Correspondence-Driven Dynamic Tri-Plane Warping for Parametric-Free Motion Control' that rethinks how motion conditions are mapped to tri-plane features in Neural Radiance Fields. Instead of modeling deformations as additive residuals or linear combinations of codewords, our method learns a set of motion-conditioned, axis-aligned warping fields that explicitly reorganize the spatial layout of tri-plane features to reflect articulated motion. These warping fields are generated by a lightweight, kernel-generating network conditioned on input motion signals (e.g., pose vectors, action labels), producing per-axis displacement maps that are applied differentiably to the canonical tri-planes via grid sampling. The key innovation lies in formulating tri-plane deformation as a dense correspondence problem in feature space—where motion induces structured spatial flows rather than simple offsets. To train this system without ground-truth 3D correspondences or parametric models, we introduce a self-supervised objective based on cycle-consistency: given two frames with swapped motion conditions, applying forward and backward warps should reconstruct the original tri-planes. Additionally, we enforce photometric and perceptual consistency in rendered views to ensure geometric plausibility. The warping fields are designed to be disentangled across tri-plane axes (XY, YZ, XZ), enabling modular control and interpretability—for instance, limb movements predominantly affect specific planes. We further enhance generalization by incorporating a meta-learning strategy where the kernel generator adapts quickly to new subjects using only a few motion-conditioned frames, making the system suitable for one-shot animation. By avoiding additive decomposition and instead performing spatial reconfiguration, our method captures non-rigid, topology-preserving transformations more faithfully than residual-based approaches. This leads to superior performance in scenarios involving large articulations, partial occlusions, or cross-category motion transfer (e.g., human-to-animal gait mimicry). Our framework supports real-time inference through cached kernel generation and low-resolution warping upscaling, and it naturally integrates with existing NeRF pipelines. Ultimately, this work establishes a new direction in 3D-aware motion control: not by modifying features, but by intelligently relocating them according to learned motion semantics—bridging the gap between correspondence learning and neural scene representation.",
